      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks, i see the issue with the delete[] now. i'll add that in. \n\nthe vector growth thing is also a good point, we have a lot of data coming in. but even with that fixed, we still had some weird spikes in memory usage yesterday that didn't quite match the expected growth curve. it's like the memory just disappears at random intervals. \n\nbesides the sanitizers, are there any other ways to track down these kinds of \"ghost\" leaks that don't show up in the obvious spots? like, how do i hunt for something that isn't immediately obvious?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Bizarre, random memory spikes that don't match your expected growth curve often point to a \"phantom\" allocation, possibly a global static variable growing over time or a library function you didn't fully control that is internalizing state. In an automotive ECU, you must also consider the specific memory constraints of your hardware; if it lacks a heap allocator, any `new` will fail silently or corrupt the heap. To hunt for these ghosts, try adding a custom `malloc` hook or a \"memory snapshot\" function that records total heap usage at every boot, every hour, and every crash to correlate timing with your spikes. If you are using a static library for your telemetry handling, ask the vendor to export their allocation symbols or check their headers for hidden global buffers. Finally, review your linker script to ensure you aren't accidentally overlapping static data sections with your dynamic heap, which can cause memory corruption that looks like a leak.",
      "source": "target",
